IFFO’s mission is to promote infrastructure investment and financing by bringing together key stakeholders. IFFO’s functions are:
- To provide a platform for information exchange and experience sharing;
- To enhance skills and knowledge in infrastructure investment and financing;
- To promote market and product development; and
- To facilitate infrastructure investment and financing activities.

The Exchange Fund Advisory Committee has set the following investment objectives for the Exchange Fund:
(a) to safeguard capital;
(b) to ensure that the overall monetary base is fully backed by highly liquid US dollar assets at all times;
(c) to ensure that liquidity is sufficient to maintain monetary and financial stability; and
(d) to maximise investment returns within the constraints of (a) to (c) above, in order to preserve the Fund’s long-term purchasing power.

The audit procedures I performed in relation to the valuation of financial assets and financial liabilities recorded at fair value included:
- Understanding the valuation processes for different categories of financial assets and financial liabilities, including related monitoring controls;
- Evaluating and testing monitoring controls, including relevant application controls in computer systems;
- Obtaining confirmations regarding the valuation, existence, rights and obligations, and completeness of financial assets and financial liabilities;
- Verifying prices against independent sources when market quotations were used;
- Assessing whether the valuation method was appropriate and whether the assumptions were reasonable when the valuation method used inputs based on observable market data, and verifying the inputs against independent sources; and
- Assessing whether the valuation method was appropriate and whether the assumptions and inputs were reasonable when the valuation method used inputs not based on observable market data.

The audit procedures I performed in relation to the Future Fund deposits included:
- Evaluating whether the accounting policies used to measure the deposits and the interest earned were appropriate;
- Reviewing the method of calculating the annual return linked to the performance of the long-term growth portfolio;
- Verifying the calculation of the fixed rate determined by reference to the past performance of the investment portfolio, the annual return linked to the performance of the long-term growth portfolio, and the composite rate determined by reference to these two rates;
- Verifying the amount of accrued interest calculated at the composite rate; and
- Reviewing the presentation and disclosure of these deposits and the interest earned in the financial statements.

As part of an audit conducted in conformity with the auditing standards of the Audit Commission, I exercise professional judgment and maintain professional scepticism throughout the audit. I also:
- Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement of the financial statements, whether due to fraud or error, design and perform audit procedures responsive to those risks, and obtain audit evidence that is sufficient and appropriate to provide a basis for my opinion. The risk of not detecting a material misstatement resulting from fraud is higher than for one resulting from error, as fraud may involve collusion, forgery, intentional omissions, misrepresentations, or the override of internal control;
- Obtain an understanding of internal control relevant to the audit in order to design audit procedures that are appropriate in the circumstances. However, this is not for the purpose of expressing an opinion on the effectiveness of the Group’s internal control;
- Evaluate the appropriateness of accounting policies used by the Financial Management Commissioner and the reasonableness of accounting estimates and related disclosures made by the Financial Management Commissioner;
- Conclude on the appropriateness of the Financial Management Commissioner’s use of the going concern basis of accounting and, based on the audit evidence obtained, whether a material uncertainty exists related to events or conditions that may cast significant doubt on the Group’s ability to continue as a going concern. If I conclude that a material uncertainty exists, I am required to draw attention in my auditor’s report to the related disclosures in the financial statements or, if such disclosures are inadequate, to modify my opinion. My conclusions are based on the audit evidence obtained up to the date of my auditor’s report. However, future events or conditions may cause the Group to cease to continue as a going concern;
- Evaluate the overall presentation, structure and content of the financial statements, including the disclosures, and whether the financial statements represent the underlying transactions and events in a manner that achieves fair presentation; and
- Obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence regarding the financial information of the entities or business activities within the Group to express an opinion on the financial statements. I am responsible for the direction, supervision and performance of the Group audit. I am solely responsible for my audit opinion.
